\begin{document}

\section*{Description of the LLM Difficulty Scoring Method}

The LLM (Language Model) difficulty scoring method is designed to objectively assess the complexity and challenges associated with a given conversational input or task. This method utilizes a structured and detailed scoring system, broken down into several specific criteria, to provide a quantitative evaluation of the difficulty. Each criterion is rated on a scale from 0 to 5, where 0 indicates no complexity and 5 indicates the highest level of complexity.

\subsection*{Criteria}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Domain Complexity (domain\_complexity)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion evaluates the complexity of the domain or field of knowledge involved in the input. Topics that are highly specialized, such as quantum physics or bioinformatics, are considered more complex compared to everyday topics.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least complex) to 5 (most complex).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Contextual Dependency (contextual\_dependency)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion assesses the extent to which the input depends on a specific context or background information. Longer and more intricate contexts increase the difficulty.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least dependent) to 5 (most dependent).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Multitasking Requirements (multitasking\_requirements)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion measures the number and complexity of tasks that need to be handled simultaneously to address the input. More complex and numerous tasks increase the difficulty.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (no multitasking) to 5 (high multitasking).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Logical Reasoning Complexity (logical\_reasoning\_complexity)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion evaluates the complexity of the logical reasoning and the number of steps required to solve the input. More intricate and multi-step reasoning increases the difficulty.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least complex) to 5 (most complex).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Language Diversity (language\_diversity)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion assesses the level of language diversity in the input, including the use of multiple natural languages or domain-specific terminology. Higher diversity increases the difficulty.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least diverse) to 5 (most diverse).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Creativity Requirements (creativity\_requirements)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion evaluates the level of creativity and innovation needed to address the input. Tasks that require more original thinking and innovative solutions are rated higher.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least creative) to 5 (most creative).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Precision and Accuracy Requirements (precision\_and\_accuracy\_requirements)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion measures the level of precision and accuracy required in the output. Tasks that demand high precision and factual accuracy are rated higher.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (least precise) to 5 (most precise).
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Model Output Constraints (model\_output\_constraints)}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Definition}: This criterion evaluates the number and strictness of constraints placed on the model's output. More constraints and strict requirements increase the difficulty.
        \item \textbf{Scoring Range}: 0 (no constraints) to 5 (most constraints).
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Scoring Process}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Input Processing}: The input is analyzed to determine its characteristics in relation to each of the eight criteria.
    \item \textbf{Scoring}: Each criterion is assigned a score between 0 and 5 based on the input's characteristics.
    \item \textbf{Output}: The scores for each criterion are compiled and returned using the "final\_result" tool. The output is a simple list of scores without any additional text or explanation.
\end{itemize}

This method ensures a systematic and objective evaluation of the difficulty associated with conversational inputs, providing a clear and quantifiable measure that can be used for further analysis and improvement of the language model's performance.

\end{document}
```

